title: nefunguje výběr článků prostředním tlačítkem (kolečkem)
content: Pravděpodobně aktualizace Firefoxu mě připravila o způsob výběru článků. Až do minulého týdne jsem např. na zpravodajském serveru vybíral články, které jsem si chtěl přečíst, kliknutím prostředního tlačítka (kolečka). Vybrané věci se zobrazily na horní liště v novém panelu, a já jsem si je postupně otvíral. Tato funkce prostředního tlačítka mi zmizela - teď musím kliknout pravým tlačítkem a vybrat "Otevřít odkaz v novém panelu". Lze nějak obnovit tuto pro mě užitečnou funkci prostředního tlačítka? Děkuji JN Dovolím si ještě vyjádřit znechucení nad programátory, kteří při aktualizaci vyřadí nějakou funkci, která je už léta používána.

title: Private Browsing Windows/Tabs as separate instances?
content:
I like using Firefox. But there is an area of my use in private browsing, where I want to have either multiple instances of windows or tabs open and they are recognised as separate browing instances.

Example of what I would like to see is, when I enter a website in private browsing, most sites would ask me to accept cookies. If I either accept or reject without closing this original another private window, it'd remember I've already chosen.

As far as I know, chrome also acts like this. But someone has pointed out Safari doesn't. I've tried it, and it does what I need. However as put in the beginning, I like using Firefox, and is wondering if anyone know if there are any plugins or settings in about:config that can make it happen?

Thank you in advance!

title: Bizarre connection throttling with google searches.
content:
I recently moved into my partners parents house temporarily and their ISP set up is less than ideal but usable. Since moving in we've had a few hiccups with the internet and initially narrowed it down to google searches.

The graphs below are my internet activity with a couple tabs open and a stream to just get a consistent graph for pre-googling and then post-googling, the connection hitching continues until i close and reopen firefox which obviously is inconvenient. (I've been making do with bing in the meantime and it is really beyond parody how bad it actually really is.)

On a whim today I tried googling something in chrome to see if it'd do the same thing and it doesn't, which is great because this went from just a bizarre isp issue to a potential bug which can hopefully be fixed.
